":"Protect","title":"Floodwalls"}}},{"node":{"id":"38db4e60-391a-5185-ac1d-505dffafd4ae","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/groynes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Groynes"}}},{"node":{"id":"1678f2e8-7dea-5a35-9e4f-7c258acc512d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/reef-systems/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Reef Systems"}}},{"node":{"id":"f578c06a-426e-5ad3-9d4a-062a6cd6c531","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/scour-protection/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Scour Protection"}}},{"node":{"id":"9886ab9a-0409-5f42-b606-4da1f6b5606d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Seawall"}}},{"node":{"id":"e503d6cd-40ad-5238-9e81-3f1fd77d864a","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/secondary-dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Secondary Dikes"}}},{"node":{"id":"35be0a4c-5325-585d-a143-1433d7cbd5b5","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Storm Surge Barriers"}}},{"node":{"id":"9d50eddd-7656-5a4d-b75b-5887ea8ad5be","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Warning System"}}},{"node":{"id":"a6e87138-5a0d-5dc6-afe8-678a851a6028","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Wet Floodproofing"}}}]}},"pageContext":{"animationSlug":"//strategies/storm-surge-barriers/animation.*png/","slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/","foo":"bar","subpages":{"benefits":"<ul>\n<li>Protects tidal inlets and estuaries from extreme wave events</li>\n<li>Reduces cost and maintenance of coastal flood defenses on the landward side</li>\n<li>Protects an entire bay area including ports. </li>\n<li>Can be utilized as a bridge or railroad link</li>\n<li>Provides infrastructure support for the development of derelict areas. </li>\n</ul>","examples":["<h3>Thames Barrier</h3>\n<h4>London ENG, UK</h4>\n<p>The Thames Barrier is one of the largest movable storm surge barriers in the world. It was constructed in response to the frequent tidal surges that London experienced before the Flood Protection Act of 1972.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> Construction began in 1974 and the finished structure was put into operation in 1982.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> According to the Environment Agency, the Thames Barrier cost around £535 million to construct. The Thames Barrier is built to provide a high level of protection for several decades. In 2000-2001 there was an unusual number of closures. Then, it was projected that the trend will continue because of climate change and sea-level rise.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup></p>","<h3>La Planche River Aboiteau</h3>\n<h4>Amherst NS, Canada</h4>\n<p>In 2015, the province of Nova Scotia awarded $5 million in the replacement of the old aboiteau on the La Planche River.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> An aboiteau is a one-way storm barrier that controls the flow of water through a dike.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> It is typically used to protect valuable assets such as marshland and agricultural land by reducing the amount of flooding during high tides or storm surges. The design and location of the new aboiteau were intended to reduce the maintenance of existing dikes and to increase the crest elevation to accommodate a rise in sea level.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> The new aboiteau is part of the 241 km of dikes and 260 aboiteau that are operated by the Agriculture Department, under the Marshlands Conservation Act. The act is intended to protect over 43,000 acres of Nova Scotia marshlands.<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup></p>"],"challenges":"<ul>\n<li>High construction and maintenance cost </li>\n<li>Affects nearby environments and transfers risk onto nearby properties and communities</li>\n<li>May negatively affect water quality in the bay area </li>\n<li>Mostly suitable for locations where inlets and narrow river mouths can be closed <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","images":["<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 481px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/d024a/Figure1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 51.767151767151766%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/d024a/Figure1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/12f09/Figure1.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/e4a3f/Figure1.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/efec03aaa67b139d47e97d60981f5d22/d024a/Figure1.png 481w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 481px) 100vw, 481px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nMaeslant barrier, Netherlands <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 370px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/1efb2/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.64864864864865%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/1efb2/Figure2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/12f09/Figure2.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/e4a3f/Figure2.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/a0732cd534e3fc1ba1f1f4867b02fff2/1efb2/Figure2.png 370w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 370px) 100vw, 370px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nHudson River Storm Surge Barriers <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 318px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/cd2d9/Figure3.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75.1572327044025%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/cd2d9/Figure3.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/12f09/Figure3.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/e4a3f/Figure3.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/129b64669ed394e2db4eb34b65d105ee/cd2d9/Figure3.png 318w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 318px) 100vw, 318px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nThames river barrier UK <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>"],"summary":"<p>Storm surge barriers are heavily engineered movable or fixed barriers/gates that are closed to prevent flooding during bad weather forecasts.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> They are commonly located across the mouth of a tidal inlet or estuaries to control the water level and prevent excessive amounts of  water from entering the estuary.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> Storm surge barriers can be very beneficial for secondary flood protection,  on the landward side of the barrier. For example, storm surge barriers can reduce the maintenance and construction cost of secondary storm protection structures.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> Because these barriers require a high level of engineering feasibility studies and because they incur high construction costs, they can be challenging to implement as a cost-effective adaptation strategy. Additionally, storm surge barriers are more appropriate in areas with tidal lets that can be closed.<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup> </p>","types":"<ul>\n<li><strong>Sector gates</strong> are radial structures comprising two gates with lateral support. Both the gates and arms create a section of a circle that turns around a vertical axis. The gates move based on the water pressure exerted against them. </li>\n<li><strong>Mitre gates</strong> are flat gates that are comprised of two units. When the two units are closed, they lean against each other forming a wedge in the direction where the water level is highest. </li>\n<li><strong>Swinging gates or barge gates</strong> are flat and rotate around a vertical axis at one side of a waterway. Swinging gates are designed to prevent tidal intrusions only in low water flow. </li>\n<li><strong>Rotary segment gates</strong> are cylindrical segments that rotate around a horizontal axis. When a rotary gate is open, the barrier rests on a sill made from concrete that is embedded in the waterway. <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> </li>\n</ul>"},"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/example1/"},"html":"<h3>The Seattle Seawall</h3>\n<p>The Seattle Seawall was originally built in 1920 and 1936, however, in 2001 and 2004, concerns about the structural integrity of the wall arose. The City of Seattle put forth the Central Seawall Project to replace the 3,700 ft of the seawall with a new seismic-resistant seawall. In addition to the state-of-the-art seawall, the project was also intended to create an unprecedented salmon migration corridor, an enhanced shoreline ecology, and an aesthetically pleasing promenade.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> The seawall features light penetrable surfaces that allow sunlight under the cantilevered where textured concrete panels and habitat benches provide habitat for juvenile salmon. </p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/image2/"},"html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 433px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/d9c5769701130cefc6188bde6d5bff83/55fc0/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.355658198614314%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/d9c5769701130cefc6188bde6d5bff83/55fc0/Figure2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/d9c5769701130cefc6188bde6d5bff83/12f09/Figure2.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/d9c5769701130cefc6188bde6d5bff83/e4a3f/Figure2.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/d9c5769701130cefc6188bde6d5bff83/55fc0/Figure2.png 433w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 433px) 100vw, 433px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nSeawalls Units Herzliya Marina <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}}}}}